{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "01 — Packages, Structs & Interfaces",
  "description": "The foundation of every Go codebase. This tour walks through internal/llm/llm.go and the start of openai.go, teaching packages, structs, struct tags, slices, and Go's interface system — all through Balaur's own model-provider seam.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 6,
      "title": "1.1 — Package declaration",
      "description": "Every `.go` file starts with a package declaration. All files in the same directory must declare the same package name — here `llm`.\n\nThe `internal/` path prefix is enforced by the Go toolchain: packages under `internal/` can **only** be imported by code that shares the parent module (`github.com/alexradunet/balaur`). It's Go's way of saying \"this is private to this repo.\"\n\nThe `llm` package today contains three files: `llm.go` (interface and types), `env.go` (the `Collect` streaming helper), and `openai.go` (the one concrete client). Local inference is served by Ollama managed in `internal/ollama`; the `llm` package is a pure HTTP client layer.\n\n**Try it:** rename the package to `llm2` in this file only and run `go build ./...`. You'll get a package-name mismatch error from Go before any other error occurs."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 11,
      "title": "1.2 — Struct and struct tags",
      "description": "```go\ntype Message struct {\n    Role       string     `json:\"role\"`\n    Content    string     `json:\"content\"`\n    ToolCalls  []ToolCall `json:\"tool_calls,omitempty\"`\n    ToolCallID string     `json:\"tool_call_id,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nA `struct` is Go's record type. No classes, no inheritance, no constructors — just named fields with types.\n\nThe backtick strings are **struct tags**: metadata attached to fields. The compiler ignores them; `encoding/json` reads them at runtime to map JSON keys to Go fields. `omitempty` means \"skip this field in JSON output if it holds its zero value\" (empty string, nil slice, etc.).\n\n**Key rule:** field names that start with an uppercase letter (`Role`, `Content`) are **exported** — visible outside the package. Lowercase names are unexported — package-private."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 19,
      "title": "1.3 — Slices",
      "description": "```go\ntype ToolCall struct {\n    ID   string `json:\"id\"`\n    Name string `json:\"name\"`\n    Args string `json:\"args\"`\n}\n```\n\nNotice `Message.ToolCalls` has type `[]ToolCall` — a **slice**. A slice is Go's dynamically-sized ordered collection, equivalent to a Python list or JS array.\n\n- `nil` is the zero value of a slice — it means \"no elements yet.\"\n- `[]ToolCall{}` is an empty (non-nil) slice.\n- `append(slice, item)` adds an element and returns the new slice.\n- `len(slice)` returns the count.\n\nThe `omitempty` tag on `ToolCalls` means a nil or empty slice is omitted from JSON — which is why messages without tool calls stay clean.\n\n**Try it:** in a scratch file, `append` a few `ToolCall` values to a nil slice and print them. Notice you never had to allocate or initialize — `append` handles it."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 33,
      "title": "1.4 — The Chunk type and multiple return values",
      "description": "```go\ntype Chunk struct {\n    Content   string\n    Reasoning string\n    ToolCalls []ToolCall\n    Done      bool\n    Err       error\n}\n```\n\nNote there are **no struct tags** here — these fields are never JSON-serialised. Struct tags are opt-in.\n\nThe `error` type is Go's built-in error interface. It has one method: `Error() string`. The zero value is `nil`, which means \"no error.\"\n\nThis struct carries everything a streaming model reply can produce: partial text, reasoning tokens, complete tool calls, a done signal, or a terminal error. A channel of `Chunk` values *is* the stream. When `Done == true` or `Err != nil`, the stream is over."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 42,
      "title": "1.5 — The Client interface (Go's most important idea)",
      "description": "```go\ntype Client interface {\n    ChatStream(ctx context.Context, msgs []Message, tools []ToolSpec) (<-chan Chunk, error)\n    Embed(ctx context.Context, texts []string) ([][]float32, error)\n}\n```\n\n**An interface in Go is just a list of method signatures.** Any type that has those methods automatically satisfies the interface — no `implements` keyword, no declaration of intent. This is called *structural typing* or *implicit satisfaction*.\n\n`kronk.Client` (a local GGUF model run in-process) satisfies `Client` because it has `ChatStream` and `Embed`; tests use a scripted fake (`internal/llmtest`) that satisfies the very same interface. The `Loop` in `internal/agent` holds a `llm.Client` and can't tell which it's talking to — that's the seam.\n\n`<-chan Chunk` is a **receive-only channel** — the type system enforces that the caller can only read from it, never write. The arrow direction is part of the type.\n\nThe `Embed` method is on the interface for completeness; it is not exercised today (embedding recall is roadmap, not shipped). Honest designs name what they intend even before the full path exists.\n\n**Exercise:** Create a type `EchoClient` in a scratch file that always returns `Chunk{Content: \"echo\", Done: true}` from `ChatStream`. Give it the right method signatures and verify it satisfies `Client` with:\n```go\nvar _ llm.Client = &EchoClient{}\n```\nIf it doesn't compile, the interface isn't satisfied."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/client.go",
      "line": 28,
      "title": "1.6 — Pointer receivers",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (c *Client) ChatStream(ctx context.Context, msgs []llm.Message, tools []llm.ToolSpec) (<-chan llm.Chunk, error) {\n    krn, err := c.eng.chatModel(ctx, c.chatPath)\n    ...\n}\n```\n\n`(c *Client)` is a **pointer receiver** — the method gets a pointer to the struct, not a copy, so it sees the actual value in memory (here, the shared `*Engine` in `c.eng`).\n\n**Value vs pointer receiver rule of thumb:** if any method on a type needs the real struct — to mutate it, or to avoid copying a struct that holds a pointer to shared state — make *all* methods pointer receivers; consistency prevents subtle bugs. Every method on `Client` and `Engine` uses a pointer receiver.\n\n`<-chan llm.Chunk` in the return type is a **receive-only channel** — the type system enforces that the caller can only read from it, never write. The arrow direction is part of the type."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/engine.go",
      "line": 106,
      "title": "1.7 — Error wrapping and defer",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (e *Engine) chatModel(ctx context.Context, ggufPath string) (*kronk.Kronk, error) {\n    e.mu.Lock()\n    defer e.mu.Unlock()\n    ...\n    krn, err := kronk.New(model.WithModelFiles([]string{ggufPath}), ...)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"loading local model %q: %w\", ggufPath, err)\n    }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nTwo Go idioms:\n\n**1. Wrap errors with `%w`.** `fmt.Errorf(\"loading local model %q: %w\", ggufPath, err)` wraps `err` with added context; the chain is preserved so `errors.Is`/`errors.As` see through it. Convention: lowercase context, no period — by the time it bubbles up it reads like a trace: `\"local chat stream: loading local model \\\"…\\\": …\"`. Use `%v` instead of `%w` when you want the message but not the chain.\n\n**2. `defer` for cleanup.** `defer e.mu.Unlock()` on the second line runs when the function returns — always, regardless of which `return` fires. It's Go's `finally`, placed right next to the `Lock()` it pairs with, so the mutex is never left held even as early returns are added later."
    }
  ]
}
